{{For|an overview of ancient watermills until 500 AD|List of ancient watermills}} [[File:Moulin maree brehat.jpg|thumb|right|[[Tide mill]]s, along with riverine [[ship mill]]s, were a major [[Early Middle Ages|early medieval]] technological advance, allowing to tap the tidal power along the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic Coast]] for milling.]]
This list of '''early medieval watermills''' comprises a selection of European [[watermill]]s spanning the [[early Middle Ages]], from 500 to 1000 AD.
== Historical overview == [[File:Shipmills, Martyrdom of St Ursula at Cologne (detail).jpg|thumb|right|[[Germany|German]] ship mills on the [[Rhine]] at [[Cologne]], around 1411.]]
Largely unaffected from the [[Migration Period|turbulent political events]] following the [[Decline of the Roman Empire|demise of the Western Roman Empire]], the importance of [[watermill]]ing continued to grow under the new [[Germanic peoples|Germanic]] lords. The sharp rise in numbers of [[Early Middle Ages|early medieval]] watermills coincided with the appearance of new documentary genres ([[legal code]]s, [[Monastery|monastic]] [[charter]]s, [[hagiography]]) which were more inclined to address such a relatively mundane device than the [[Classical antiquity|ancient]] urban-centered literary class had been.<ref>{{harvnb|Wilson|2002|p=3}}</ref> This partly explains the relative abundance of medieval literary references to watermills compared to former times.<ref>{{harvnb|Wikander|2000|pp=372f.}}</ref>
The quantitative growth of medieval evidence appears to be more than a mere reflection of the changing nature of surviving sources. By [[Carolingian dynasty|Carolingian]] times, references to watermills in the [[Carolingian Empire|Frankish Realm]] had become "innumerable".<ref name="Wikander 1985, 170, 45"/> At the time of the compilation of the [[Domesday Book]] (1086), there were an estimated 6,500 watermills in [[Norman England|England]] alone.<ref>{{harvnb|Holt|1988|pp=7–8, 11}}</ref>
By the early 7th century, watermills were well established in [[Ireland]], and began to spread from the former territory of the empire into the non-romanized parts of [[Germany]] a century later.<ref>{{harvnb|Wikander|2000|p=400}}</ref> The introduction of the [[ship mill]] and [[tide mill]] in the 6th century, both of which yet unattested for the ancient period,<ref>{{harvnb|Wikander|2000|pp=379 & 383f.}}</ref> allowed for a flexible response to the changing water-level of rivers and the [[Atlantic Ocean]], thus demonstrating the technological innovativeness of early medieval watermillers.
