[[File:Traditional Trug.jpg|thumb|A Sussex trug]] A '''Sussex trug''' is a wooden [[basket]]. It is made from a handle and rim of [[coppicing|coppiced]] [[Castanea sativa|sweet chestnut]] wood which is hand-cleft then shaved using a [[drawknife]]. The body of the trug is made of five or seven thin boards of [[Salix alba#Cultivars and hybrids|cricket bat willow]], also hand-shaved with a drawknife.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.countrylovers.co.uk/craf/susxtrug.htm |title=Images of trug making| publisher=countrylovers.co.uk }}</ref> They may have originated in Sussex because of the abundance of chestnut coppice and willows found on the marshes. Nails or pins used are usually copper, to avoid rust.
Shapes and sizes became standardised, the most well-known shape being the "common or garden" trug ranging in volume from [[dry measure|one pint to a bushel]]. However, there is a diverse range of traditional trugs from garden and oval trugs to the more specialised "large log" and "walking stick" trugs.<ref>[http://www.thetrugstore.co.uk/handmadesussextrugproducts.html#WalkingStickTrugAnchor Image of a "walking stick" trug] from thetrugstore.co.uk</ref>
==History== Richard Acres worked as a trug maker in 1485, in Rotherfield in Sussex.<ref> Plea Rolls of the Court of Common Pleas; CP 40/891; reign of Richard III; http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT3/R3/CP40no891/aCP40no891fronts/IMG_0171.htm 4th entry, with Kent in the margin</ref>
Trugs date back to the [[1500s in England|1500s]],<ref name="guard09">{{cite web| title=How to make a trug | url= https://www.theguardian.com/money/2009/oct/03/make-a-trug-sussex-basket| date=2 October 2009 | first= Jon|last= Henley| accessdate= 2013-03-11| publisher= [[The Guardian]]}}</ref> with active trade in [[Horsham]].<ref>{{cite web| title=A History of the County of Sussex: Volume 6 Part 2: Bramber Rape (North-Western Part) including Horsham | url= http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=18352 | year=1986 | editor=T. P. Hudson | accessdate= 2013-03-11| quote=Already by the 16th century there were representatives of more specialized trades, reflecting the high social and economic status of many of the town's residents: an armourer, a barber, a cutler, a foyster or maker of saddle trees, a hat dresser, a last maker, a painter, and makers of buckets, pins, points (i.e. fastenings for clothes), scythes, baskets or trugs, and shovels.}}</ref>
Thomas Smith of [[Herstmonceux]], displaying his trugs at the [[Great Exhibition of 1851]], gave the basket wider renown;<ref name="guard09"/> he was rewarded when [[Queen Victoria]] purchased several for members of the [[British Royal Family|Royal family]].<ref name="trugfair">{{cite web|url=http://www.greenchronicle.com/garden_trugs2.htm|title=Sussex Garden Trug|accessdate=10 March 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319214644/http://www.greenchronicle.com/garden_trugs2.htm|archivedate=19 March 2012|df=}}</ref> Further appearances at international exhibitions followed at the 1855 [[Exposition Universelle (1855)|Universal exhibition]] in Paris; the [[First International Forestry Exhibition]] in Edinburgh 1884 and London [[International Inventions Exhibition]].<ref name="trugfair" />
By the 1970s, Herstmonceux remained as a significant centre of trug production, with four firms operating [[Wealden District|in or near]] that village: Greens of Hailsham, R. Reed, R.W. Rich and Sons, and Thomas Smith and Sons.<ref name="Tuffin71">{{cite web| title=The Sussex Trug: An Investigation into the Production of Trugs | url= http://oldsca.lib.liv.ac.uk/~cheshire/cgi-bin/leedssearch.cgi?bool=AND&numreq=1&fieldcont1=component1_db:5000&format=full&components=0&fieldidx1=componentid&scanposition=middle&firstrec=1&ratio=2.000000| year=1971 | last= Tuffin| first=Alison| accessdate= 2013-03-11| quote= A study of trug making in Sussex, with particular reference to four firms operating in and around the village of Herstmonceux. The first of nine chapters provides a general introduction, followed by a history of the trug, and its inventor Thomas Smith. Further chapters describe the manufacture of trugs, their sale and usage, the craftsmen who made-make them, mechanisation and its influence on the trug industry, and descriptions of four trugging firms (Greens of Hailsham, R. Reed, R.W. Rich and Sons and Thomas Smith and Sons).}}</ref>
